'''Takefusa Kubo'''{{efn|{{langx|ja|久保 建英}}, [[Hepburn romanization|Hepburn]]: {{transliteration|ja|Kubo Takefusa}}, {{IPA|ja|kɯbo takeɸɯsa|IPA}}}} (born 4 June 2001), commonly known as '''Take Kubo''', is a Japanese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder (association football)#Winger|right winger]] for [[La Liga]] club [[Real Sociedad]] and the [[Japan national football team|Japan national team]].<ref name=JL>{{cite web | url=https://data.j-league.or.jp/SFIX04/?player_id=19690 | language=ja | title=久保 建英 Takefusa KUBO, referred to as 'Japanese Messi' | publisher=J.League Data Site | access-date=6 December 2016 }}</ref><ref name="transfer">{{cite news|url=https://www.realsociedad.eus/en/news/details/he-is-finally-here|title=He is finally here|publisher=Real Sociedad|date=19 July 2022|access-date=9 December 2023}}</ref> He has been dubbed "Japanese [[Lionel Messi|Messi]]" by Japanese football fans because of his technical ability.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid sign 'Japanese Messi' Kubo |url=https://www.the-afc.com/en/more/news/real_madrid_sign_japanese_messi_kubo.html |date=14 June 2019 |access-date=10 January 2024 |publisher=Asian Football Confederation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=TIMES編集部 |first=ABEMA |date=2025-03-20 |title=「日本のメッシ！」久保建英のスーパーゴールにSNS衝撃！「天才だよほんとに」「嘘だろ上手すぎる」「うまっ」GK欺いてぶち抜いた完璧ショットの瞬間 {{!}} サッカー日本代表 {{!}} ABEMA TIMES {{!}} アベマタイムズ |url=https://times.abema.tv/articles/-/10169528 |access-date=2026-05-19 |website=ABEMA TIMES |language=ja}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
At the age of seven, Takefusa Kubo started playing football for some local clubs in his hometown, [[Kawasaki, Kanagawa|Kawasaki]]. In August 2009, he was awarded the MVP at FC Barcelona Soccer Camp in which he participated at the age of eight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kaptivasportsexperience.com/|title=Kaptiva Sports Experience football|website=Kaptiva Sports Experience|language=en-GB|access-date=24 August 2019|archive-date=2 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402151859/https://kaptivasportsexperience.com/|url-status=dead}}</ref> In April 2010, he was selected as a member of FC Barcelona School team and participated in Sodexo European Rusas Cup held in Belgium. He was awarded MVP even though his team finished third. After returning home, he began to play for the [[Kawasaki Frontale]] junior youth team.

===Barcelona===
In August 2011, Takefusa Kubo had been invited to join FC Barcelona's youth Academy, [[La Masia]], after passing the trial. He began to play for [[La Masia|Barca Aleví C]] (U11). During his first full season (2012–13), he was top goalscorer in the league with 74 goals in 30 games. In his third full season (2014–15), he was promoted to [[La Masia|Barca Infantil A]] (U14). The Spanish club was later found to have violated FIFA's international transfer policy for under-18 youths, making Kubo ineligible to play for the club. He returned to Japan in March 2015 in search of playing time, signing with [[FC Tokyo]]’s junior youth team.

===FC Tokyo===
Takefusa Kubo joined [[FC Tokyo]] U-18 team in 2016. In September 2016, he was promoted to the senior side at the age of fifteen. On 5 November, he made his formal debut for the reserve team in the [[J3 League]] as a halftime sub for match against [[AC Nagano Parceiro]].<ref name=JL /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.j-league.or.jp/SFMS02/?match_card_id=18885|title=J. League Data Site|website=data.j-league.or.jp|access-date=24 August 2019}}</ref> He made his professional debut at the [[J.League]] record of 15 years, five months and one day.

On 15 April 2017 Kubo became the youngest player to score in the [[J.League]] at 15 years, ten months in a 1–0 win over [[Cerezo Osaka|Cerezo Osaka U-23]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jleague.jp/match/j3/2017/041511/recap/|title=Ｃ大23vsＦ東23のマッチレポート・動画（明治安田生命Ｊ３リーグ第5節：2017年4月15日）：Ｊリーグ.jp|trans-title=The match report and the video of Cerezo Osaka U-23 vs FC Tokyo U-23 (Meiji Yasuda Seimei J3 league Sec 5, 15 April 2017)|website=Ｊリーグ.jp（日本プロサッカーリーグ）|language=ja|access-date=24 August 2019}}</ref> On 3 May, he top-flight debuted for the first-team in [[J.League Cup|J.League YBC Levain Cup]] playing 25 minutes in a 1–0 win against [[Hokkaido Consadole Sapporo]].
In November 2017, FC Tokyo announced an update to Kubo's contract improving it to pay him as a first-team member.

====Yokohama F. Marinos (loan)====
On 16 August 2018, he joined [[Yokohama F. Marinos]] on a half-year loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f-marinos.com/news/detail/2018-08-16/083000/194816|title=久保建英選手 期限付き移籍加入のお知らせ|publisher=Yokohama F. Marinos|date=16 August 2018|access-date=16 August 2018|archive-date=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816194635/http://www.f-marinos.com/news/detail/2018-08-16/083000/194816|url-status=dead}}</ref> He immediately scored on his debut with ''Marinos'' in an away game against [[Vissel Kobe]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/jp/%E3%83%8B%E3%83%A5%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B9/%E9%95%B7%E5%8F%8B%E4%BD%91%E9%83%BDj1%E5%88%9D%E3%82%B4%E3%83%BC%E3%83%AB%E3%81%AE%E4%B9%85%E4%BF%9D%E5%BB%BA%E8%8B%B1%E3%81%AB%E9%A9%9A%E3%81%8D%E3%81%AE%E5%A3%B0%E3%82%8215%E6%AD%B3%E3%81%A7%E7%82%B9%E5%8F%96%E3%81%A3%E3%81%A6%E3%82%8B%E5%8C%96%E7%89%A9%E3%81%8C%E3%81%84%E3%81%9F/13y43ik4f4xi11xetqvcf4bn3n |title=長友佑都、J1初ゴールの久保建英に驚きの声も「15歳で点取ってる化物がいた」 &#124; Goal.com |access-date=28 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827115513/http://www.goal.com/jp/%E3%83%8B%E3%83%A5%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B9/%E9%95%B7%E5%8F%8B%E4%BD%91%E9%83%BDj1%E5%88%9D%E3%82%B4%E3%83%BC%E3%83%AB%E3%81%AE%E4%B9%85%E4%BF%9D%E5%BB%BA%E8%8B%B1%E3%81%AB%E9%A9%9A%E3%81%8D%E3%81%AE%E5%A3%B0%E3%82%8215%E6%AD%B3%E3%81%A7%E7%82%B9%E5%8F%96%E3%81%A3%E3%81%A6%E3%82%8B%E5%8C%96%E7%89%A9%E3%81%8C%E3%81%84%E3%81%9F/13y43ik4f4xi11xetqvcf4bn3n |archive-date=27 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

From the start of the 2019 season, Kubo became a regular starter for FC Tokyo in both the [[J.League Cup|J.League YBC Levain Cup]] and J.League scoring goals in both competitions.

===Real Madrid===
On 14 June 2019, Kubo signed with Spanish club [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] on a five-year deal. Although registered with their [[Real Madrid CF (youth)|U-19 team]],<ref>{{cite news|date=17 July 2019|title=Kubo set to be registered by Real Madrid as youth team player|url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/07/17/football/1563349662_628825.html|publisher=[[Diario AS]]|access-date=17 July 2019|archive-date=4 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804105043/https://en.as.com/en/2019/07/17/football/1563349662_628825.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> he had been expected to mainly play for [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]] during the 2019–20 season.<ref>{{cite news |date=14 June 2019 |title=Takefusa Kubo is a new Real Madrid player. He joins Castilla from next season |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2019/06/takefusa-kubo-is-a-new-real-madrid-player-he-joins-castilla-from-next-season |publisher=[[Real Madrid]] |access-date=14 June 2019}}</ref> However, he featured regularly with the first team during Real Madrid's preseason tour of the United States and Germany.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kubo: "I'm unhappy with the result but pleased to have made my debut"|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2019/07/kubo-im-unhappy-with-the-result-but-pleased-to-have-made-my-debut|publisher=realmadrid.com |date=21 July 2019 |access-date=21 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2019/10/18/5da8f877268e3eec168b45d0.html|title=Kubo: I signed for Real Madrid because they had a plan for my future|date=18 October 2019|website=MARCA in English|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref>

====Mallorca (loan)====
On 22 August 2019, Kubo joined [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] on a season-long loan,<ref>{{cite news |title=Kubo joins RCD Mallorca on loan from Real Madrid|url=http://www.rcdmallorca.es/en/content/news/news/kubo-joins-rcd-mallorca-on-loan-from-real-madrid|publisher=rcdmallorca.es |date=22 August 2019 |access-date=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Official Announcement: Kubo|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2019/08/official-announcement-kubo|publisher=realmadrid.com |date=22 August 2019 |access-date=22 August 2019}}</ref> becoming the third Japanese player in Mallorca history after [[Yoshito Ōkubo]] and [[Akihiro Ienaga]]. On 1 September, he made his [[La Liga]] debut, playing 15 minutes in a 2–0 loss to [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]. He became the youngest Japanese player in the Top 4 European leagues<!--France hasn't always been included in the Big Five; if/when that history is added to [[Big Five (association football)]], suggest wikilink--> history that has played in a match with a record of 18 years, 2 months, and 28 days.{{citation needed|date=July 2020}} On 10 November, he scored his first goal for the club in a 3–1 victory against [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-11-10 |title=Real Madrid loanee Takefusa Kubo scores brilliant first LaLiga goal for Mallorca |url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/11/10/soccer/1573388916_113423.html |access-date=2024-03-04 |website=Diario AS |language=en-us}}</ref> He later scored his second goal in an entertaining 3–3 draw to [[Real Betis]] on 21 February 2020. Two weeks later, he scored a game-winner in a 2–1 victory over [[SD Eibar|Eibar]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 March 2020 |title=Mallorca 2-1 Eibar |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/550349 |access-date=2024-03-04 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

====Loans to Villarreal and Getafe====
On 10 August 2020, he was loaned to [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] until the end of the 2020–21 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/news/item/28296-welcome-kubo|title=Welcome Kubo!|publisher=villarrealcf.es|date=10 August 2020|access-date=10 August 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2020/08/10/official-announcement-kubo|title=Official Announcement: Kubo|publisher=realmadrid.com|date=10 August 2020|access-date=10 August 2020}}</ref> After being mainly used as a substitute, his loan was cut short on 8 January 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/news/item/29512-official-announcement-take-kubo|title=Official announcement: Take Kubo|publisher=Villarreal CF|date=8 January 2021|access-date=8 January 2021}}</ref>

Immediately after leaving Villarreal, Kubo moved to fellow top-tier side [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] on loan for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2021/01/08/official-announcement-takefusa-kubo|title=Official Announcement: Takefusa Kubo|publisher=Real Madrid|date=8 January 2021|access-date=8 January 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=COMUNICADO OFICIAL: Take Kubo|url=https://www.getafecf.com/Noticia/tabid/137/Article/7256/COMUNICADO-OFICIAL-Take-Kubo.aspx|access-date=8 January 2021|publisher=getafecf.com}}</ref>

====Return to Mallorca====
On 12 August 2021, Kubo rejoined [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Official Announcement: Kubo |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2021/08/11/official-announcement-kubo |access-date=11 August 2021 |website=Real Madrid C.F.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Take Kubo returns to RCD Mallorca |url=https://www.rcdmallorca.es/en/content/news/news/take-kubo-returns-to-rcd-mallorca |access-date=11 August 2021 |publisher=rcdmallorca.es}}</ref> On 4 December, Kubo scored a stoppage-time winner in a 2–1 victory at the [[Wanda Metropolitano]] against [[Atlético Madrid]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 December 2021 |title=Real Madrid loanee scores stoppage-time winner for Mallorca at Atletico |url=https://www.espn.com/watch/player/_/id/32787462 |access-date=2024-03-04 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

=== Real Sociedad ===
On 19 July 2022, Kubo joined [[Real Sociedad]] on a permanent deal, becoming the first Japanese player to sign with the club.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 July 2022 |title=Ya está aquí |url=https://www.realsociedad.eus/es/noticias/detalle/ya-esta-aqui-8 |access-date=19 July 2022 |website=Real Sociedad |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=19 July 2022 |title=Kubo becomes 1st Japanese player to join Real Sociedad |url=https://www.laprensalatina.com/kubo-becomes-1st-japanese-player-to-join-real-sociedad/ |access-date=19 July 2022 |website=Real Sociedad |language=es |archive-date=4 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240304215159/https://www.laprensalatina.com/kubo-becomes-1st-japanese-player-to-join-real-sociedad/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Official Announcement: Kubo|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2022/07/19/official-announcement-kubo|publisher=Real Madrid CF|date=19 July 2022|access-date=19 July 2022}}</ref> Kubo marked his debut by scoring the only goal in a 1–0 win away to [[Cádiz CF|Cádiz]] in their opening game of the season in La Liga.<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 August 2022 |title=Japan star Kubo nets winner on Real Sociedad debut |url=https://www.rfi.fr/en/sports/20220814-japan-star-kubo-nets-winner-on-real-sociedad-debut |access-date=14 August 2022 |website=RFI |language=en}}</ref> On 18 September 2023, Kubo's adept performance against his former club Real Madrid earned him recognition despite Real Sociedad's 2–1 defeat.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-18 |title=Real Madrid 2-1 Real Sociedad |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/674058 |access-date=2023-11-05 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=2023-09-18 |title=Takefusa Kubo's star performance not enough against Real Madrid |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2023/09/18/soccer/kubo-sociedad-lose-madrid/ |access-date=2023-11-05 |website=The Japan Times |language=en}}</ref> On 22 October 2023, Kubo was instrumental in leading Real Sociedad to a 1–0 win over Mallorca, earning the man-of-the-match title for his performance.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-10-22 |title=Football: Kubo sets up winner as Sociedad beat Mallorca 1-0 |url=https://www.nippon.com/en/news/kd1088679347195347441/ |access-date=2023-11-05 |website=Nippon |language=en |archive-date=5 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231105053612/https://www.nippon.com/en/news/kd1088679347195347441/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=2023-10-22 |title=Takefusa Kubo sets up winner as Sociedad beats Mallorca |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2023/10/22/soccer/kubo-sociedad-mallorca-assist/ |access-date=2023-11-05 |website=The Japan Times |language=en}}</ref>

On 18 April 2026 Kubo came off the bench in the 88th minute as Real Sociedad beat [[Atlético Madrid|Atletico Madrid]] on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]] to win the [[Copa del Rey]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=MacDonald |first=Live ReportingKeifer |title=Atletico Madrid 2-2 Real Sociedad (3-4 on pens): Sociedad triumph to win fourth Copa del Rey title |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cy0130ned7yt |access-date=2026-05-13 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==International career==
Kubo has been involved in [[Japan national football team|Japan]] national teams from U-15 to senior level. At the age of fifteen, he was selected to the [[Japan national under-20 football team|Japan U-20 national team]] for the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfa.jp/eng/news/00013400/|title=U-20 Japan National Team squad, schedule – FIFA U-20 World Cup Korea Republic 2017 (5/20-6/11)|work=[[Japan Football Association|JFA]]|access-date=2 May 2017}}</ref>

Shortly before turning eighteen, Kubo was named in the squad for the [[2019 Copa América]], which marked his first call up to the senior squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2019/05/23/soccer/takefusa-kubo-17-named-japans-senior-national-squad-first-time|title=Takefusa Kubo, 17, named to Japan's senior national squad for first time|work=[[Japan Times]]|date=23 May 2019|access-date=5 June 2019}}</ref> He made his debut on 9 June 2019 in a friendly against El Salvador, as a 67th-minute substitute for [[Takumi Minamino]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match?gameId=539195|title=Japan v El Salvador game report|date=9 June 2019}}</ref> In July 2021, he was included in the 22-player squad of the [[Japan national under-23 football team|under-23 team]] for the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u24_2021/news/00027265/| title= U-24 Japan National Team Squad - Games of the XXXII Olympiad (Tokyo 2020)【7/21-8/7】, KIRIN CHALLENGE CUP 2021【7/12＠Osaka, 7/17＠Hyogo】| date= 22 June 2021| website= www.jfa.jp| publisher= [[Japan Football Association|Japan Football Association (JFA)]]| language= en| access-date= 22 June 2021}}</ref>

On 22 July 2021, Kubo scored Japan's first goal against [[South Africa national under-23 soccer team|South Africa]] in the 2020 Olympics.<ref>Football - Japan vs South Africa - Group A Results [https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/results-men-gpa-000200-.htm] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210721200541/https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/results-men-gpa-000200-.htm|date=21 July 2021}}</ref>

On 1 November 2022, Kubo was named in the Japan squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jfa.jp/eng/samuraiblue/news/00030869/ |title=Samurai Blue (Japan National Team) squad – FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022 |publisher=[[Japan Football Association]] |date=1 November 2022 |access-date=1 November 2022}}</ref> where he started in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup Group E|group stage]] victories over [[Germany national football team|Germany]]<ref>{{Cite news |title=Germany stunned by late Japan comeback |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63644792 |access-date=1 December 2022}}</ref> and [[Spain national football team|Spain]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=Japan and Spain both through on dramatic night |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63739246 |access-date=1 December 2022}}</ref> despite being subbed off early in both matches.

==Personal life==
Kubo speaks Spanish fluently.{{citation needed|date=May 2026}}

